04763nam a22006975i 9780824853860DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248538607 a10.1515/97808248538602doi  a(DE-B1597)484074  a(OCoLC)905734207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0230002bisacsh04a305.40951952231 aLee, Ji-Eun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen Pre-Scripted :bForging Modern Roles through Korean Print /cJi-Eun Lee. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b13 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface And Acknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Women in Book Culture -- tChapter Two. Conceiving Women’s Issues -- tChapter Three. Project Woman, Destination Home -- tChapter Four. By Woman’s Hand -- tChapter Five. Colony, Modernity, and Sinyŏsŏng (1923–1 934) -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen Pre-Scripted explores the way ideas about women and their social roles changed during Korea's transformation into a modern society. Drawing on a wide range of materials published in periodicals—ideological debates, cartoons, literary works, cover illustrations, letters and confessions--the author shows how at different times between 1896 and 1934, the idea of modern womanhood transforms from virgin savior to mother of the nation to manager of modern family life and, finally, to an embodiment of the capitalist West, fully armed with sexuality and glamour.Each chapter examines representative periodicals to explore how their content on a range of women's issues helped formulate and prescribe women's roles, defining what would later become appropriate knowledge for women in the new modern context. Lee shows how in various ways this prescribing was gendered, how it would sometimes promote the "modern" and at other times critique it. She offers a close look at primary sources not previously introduced in English, exploring the subject and genre of each work, the script used, and the way it categorized or defined a given women's issue. By identifying and dissecting the various agendas and agents behind the scenes, she is able to shed light on the complex and changing relationship between domesticity, gender, and modernity during Korea's transition to a modern state and its colonial occupation. Women Pre-Scripted contributes to the swell of research on Asian women in recent years and expands our picture of a complex period. It will be of interest to scholars of Korean literature and history, East Asian literature, and others interested in women and gender within the context of colonial modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSex rolezKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxPress coveragezKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's periodicals, KoreanxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485386040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824853860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824853860.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  a